SENATE RESOLUTION NO. 107
BY SENATOR BOUDREAUX
A RESOLUTION
To express the sincere condolences of the Senate of the Legislature of Louisiana upon the
death of Joel Parker Sr.
WHEREAS, it is with deep regret and profound sorrow that the citizens of Louisiana
learned of the peaceful transition into eternal life of Joel Parker Sr. on April 17, 2026, at the
age of eighty-nine; and
WHEREAS, Joel Parker Sr., was born on March 23, 1937, to Ezola Young in
Washington, Louisiana, where he accepted Christ and was baptized at an early age, and
served as a devoted member of Wiley United Methodist Church in Blanks, Louisiana; and
WHEREAS, Joel Parker Sr. was united in holy matrimony to Elnora Murray on
January 21, 1960, with their union being blessed with four daughters and two sons and they
shared thirty-five years of love and devotion until her passing on June 3, 1995; and
WHEREAS, he developed a passion for horses at a young age and became known
as one of the finest cowboys, horse trainers, and rodeo event presenters with himself having
competed in rodeos as a saddle bronc rider and bull rider; and
WHEREAS, despite the challenges of not being welcome as a black cowboy, Joel
fought against the odds and became a Stock and Rodeo Producer in Louisiana and
Mississippi, bringing black and white cowboys together; and
WHEREAS, for over fifty years Joel hosted rodeos where he was recognized as a
strong inspiration to the many young people involved in his rodeos at the Lottie Stampede
Arena, alongside his sons and rodeo partner, Eli Allen. Their Easter Sunday Rodeo became
a cherished family tradition for many years; and
WHEREAS, Joel Parker Sr. was a faithful and hardworking man who worked for the
Weinstein' Haas-Herschel Ranch; the JE Jumonville Ranch; the OD Kent Ranch; and later
retired from the Alma Plantation in early 2000; and
WHEREAS, Joel leaves behind many cherished memories for his family and friends
